Aging: damage accumulation versus increasing mortality rate.

Finkelstein M(1).

Author information:
(1)Department of Mathematical Statistics, University of Free State, PO Box 339, 
9300 Bloemfontein, South Africa. FinkelM@sci.uovs.ac.za

If aging is understood as some process of damage accumulation, it does not 
necessarily lead to increasing mortality rate. Within the framework of a 
suggested generalization of the Strehler-Mildwan (1960) [B.L. Strehler, A.S. 
Mildvan (1960). General theory of mortality and aging, Science, 132, 14] model, 
we show that even for models with monotonically increasing degradation, the 
mortality rate can still decrease. The decline in vitality and functions, as 
manifestation of aging, is modeled by the monotonically decreasing quality of 
life function. Using this function, the initial lifetime random variable with 
ultimately decreasing mortality rate is 'weighted' to result in a new random 
variable, which is already characterized by the increasing mortality rate.

