The prevalence of patients with chronic kidney disease (CKD) in the US 
population is approximately 11%, and because of the increase in life expectancy 
and in diabetic nephropathy incidence, an exponential increase is predicted for 
the next decades. During the past decade, evidence that the progression of CKD 
can be attenuated by a multifactorial therapeutic approach has been increasing. 
However, a substantial percentage of patients with CKD will have progression to 
CKD stage V (ie, need for renal replacement therapy). Late referral of these 
patients (ie, <1 to 6 months before the start of renal replacement therapy) has 
been shown to be associated with higher mortality, morbidity, and costs. 
However, up to 64% of patients with CKD are still referred late. This review 
presents the available data on the epidemiology, causes, and consequences of 
late patient referral. Furthermore, it offers information to prevent late 
referral, improve CKD patient care, and change clinical practice.

